From the point at which we recover the guidance of Tacitus all the rest of his narrative is little more than that of a prolonged reign of terror.

Tiberius is rhetorically described as never tired of trials and con· demnations and never satiated ⁸, even stimulated by them to further camage⁸, like a wild beast who has tasted blood.
